Types of Arrays in C
Type	Description
1. One-Dimensional (1D) Array	Stores data in a single row or line (like a list).
2. Two-Dimensional (2D) Array	Stores data in rows and columns (like a table or matrix).
3. Multi-Dimensional Array	Arrays with more than 2 dimensions (used rarely).
One-Dimensional (1D) Array Example
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int i;
    int marks[5] = {85, 90, 78, 92, 88};  // 1D array declaration and initialization

    printf("Marks of 5 students:\n");
    for(i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        printf("Student %d: %d\n", i + 1, marks[i]);
    }

    return 0;
}
Explanation:

int marks[5]; → creates an array of 5 integers.

marks[i] → accesses the element at position i (index starts from 0).

The loop prints all array elements.
Two-Dimensional (2D) Array Example
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int i, j;
    int matrix[2][3] = { {1, 2, 3}, {4, 5, 6} };  // 2D array initialization (2 rows, 3 columns)

    printf("Matrix elements are:\n");
    for(i = 0; i < 2; i++) {
        for(j = 0; j < 3; j++) {
            printf("%d ", matrix[i][j]);
        }
        printf("\n");  // new line after each row
    }

    return 0;
}
Explanation:

int matrix[2][3]; → declares a 2D array with 2 rows and 3 columns.

matrix[i][j] → accesses the element in the ith row and jth column.

Nested for loops print all elements row by row.
